%S A396785 17,103,211,499,691,967,1093,1217,1489,1777,2131,2657,2707,2887,2897,
%T A396785 3463,3571,3613,3793,3847,4657,4723,5011,5233,5521,5683,6343,6547,
%U A396785 6977,7027,7411,7603,7699,7933,8167,8179,8467,8689,9043,9377,9619,9907,10567,10663
%N A396785 Primes that do not appear at division steps of A381466.
%C A396785 a(n) is the n-th prime number p such that A381466(k*p) != p for all k greater than 1. It is impossible for a number N to appear in A381466 after term N*(6N - 2), so there is no need to check past k = 6p - 2.
%C A396785 The product of any two terms in this sequence (e.g., 17*17 = 289 or 103*211 = 21733) is necessarily an addition step of A381466, since, if it was a division step, the term at that step would have to be one of the two primes in its factorization, which is a contradiction.
%C A396785 We conjecture that there are infinitely many terms in this sequence. If this is true, then there exist infinitely many odd semiprimes that are addition steps, which, along with all odd primes and their squares, would be another infinite collection of odd addition steps that is "reasonably describable".
%C A396785 17, 499, 967, and 1217 do not appear in A381466 at all, and so they appear in A381501.
%C A396785 103, 211, 691, and 1093 are terms at addition steps of A381466 and, as such, do not appear in A381501.
%o A396785 (PARI) lista(nn) = my(lim=nn*(6*nn-2), v = vector(lim), vp=List()); v[1] = 4; for (n=2, lim, my(g=gcd(v[n-1], n-1)); if (g==1, v[n] = v[n-1] + n-1, v[n] = (n-1)/g; if (isprime(v[n]) && !vecsearch(vp, v[n]), listput(vp, v[n]); listsort(vp)); ); ); select(x->(x<=nn), setminus(primes(primepi(vecmax(vp))), Vec(vp))); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Jun 08 2026
%Y A396785 Cf. A381466, A381501.
%K A396785 nonn
